===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|犬|t1=dog|自|t2=nose|ls=ic}}, referring to the dog's strong sense of smell. Original form of {{och-l|嗅|to smell}}.

===Etymology===
{{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} considers it to be cognate with {{och-l|犨|sound of an ox breathing}} and connects it to {{cog|my|ဟိုက်||to pant}}.

Also compare {{och-l|朽|to rot; to decay}} ({{zh-ref|Baxter and Sagart, 2014}}).

